Note: ========================================
Note: OpenAPI Translator Tests
Note: ========================================
Note: Comprehensive test suite for OpenAPI/Swagger translation system

Note: Test Coverage:
Note:   - Parser validation tests (required fields, structure)
Note:   - OpenAPI→HIR translation tests
Note:   - HIR→OpenAPI generation tests
Note:   - Round-trip translation tests
Note:   - Semantic preservation tests
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/openapi/openapi_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/openapi/openapi_to_hir.runa" as ToHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/openapi/hir_to_openapi.runa" as FromHIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: ========================================
Note: Test Runner
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver for the OpenAPI translator suite. Runs four parser
tests (minimal spec, info validation, paths, components), to-HIR,
from-HIR, and round-trip.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print banner, call each test_* proc serially. Failures reported
inline by assert_* helpers.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 7 tests print "[OK]" -> clean suite
- Any assert_* failure prints "FAILED:" -> visible in CI
@End TestCases

Process called "run_all_openapi_tests":
    Note: Run complete OpenAPI test suite

    proc print_string with "OpenAPI Translator Test Suite"
    proc print_newline

    proc test_parser_minimal
    proc test_parser_info_validation
    proc test_parser_paths
    proc test_parser_components
    proc test_openapi_to_hir
    proc test_hir_to_openapi
    proc test_round_trip

    proc print_newline
    proc print_string with "All OpenAPI tests completed!"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Parser Validation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser accepts the minimal OpenAPI 3.0.0 specification:
openapi version, info block (title + version), and an empty paths
object. This is the lowest-common-denominator spec; failure here
breaks all subsequent tests.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Build minimal YAML spec.
2. parse_openapi(spec) -> ast; assert not null.
3. Assert ast has top-level "openapi", "info", and "paths" keys.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Minimal spec -> non-null AST with all three required fields, passed
- Missing "openapi" key -> "Has openapi version" fails
- Missing "info" key -> "Has info object" fails
- Missing "paths" key -> "Has paths object" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_minimal":
    Note: Test minimal valid OpenAPI specification

    proc print_string with "Testing minimal OpenAPI parsing..."

    Note: Minimal OpenAPI 3.0.0 spec
    Let minimal_spec be proc create_string_literal with "openapi: 3.0.0\ninfo:\n  title: Test API\n  version: 1.0.0\npaths: {}\n"

    Let ast be proc parse_openapi from Parser with minimal_spec

    Note: Should parse successfully
    proc assert_not_null with ast, "Minimal spec parsed"

    Note: Check required fields
    Let openapi_key be proc create_string_literal with "openapi"
    Let openapi_version be proc get from Dict with ast, openapi_key
    proc assert_not_null with openapi_version, "Has openapi version"

    Let info_key be proc create_string_literal with "info"
    Let info_obj be proc get from Dict with ast, info_key
    proc assert_not_null with info_obj, "Has info object"

    Let paths_key be proc create_string_literal with "paths"
    Let paths_obj be proc get from Dict with ast, paths_key
    proc assert_not_null with paths_obj, "Has paths object"

    proc print_string with "  ✓ Minimal OpenAPI parsing tests passed"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles an info object with optional fields
(description, contact subblock with name+email). Catches a
regression where the parser is overly strict about unknown keys.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parse a spec with the full info block. Assert ast not null. Look
up info.title and info.version; assert both non-null.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Full info block -> non-null AST with title and version, passed
- Parser rejects "contact" subblock -> ast == 0 -> "Valid info parsed" fails
- info.title missing -> "Info has title" fails
- info.version missing -> "Info has version" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_info_validation":
    Note: Test info object validation

    proc print_string with "Testing info object validation..."

    Note: Valid info object
    Let valid_spec be proc create_string_literal with "openapi: 3.0.0\ninfo:\n  title: My API\n  version: 1.0.0\n  description: Test API description\n  contact:\n    name: API Support\n    email: support@example.com\npaths: {}\n"

    Let ast be proc parse_openapi from Parser with valid_spec

    Note: Should parse successfully
    proc assert_not_null with ast, "Valid info parsed"

    Note: Check info fields
    Let info_key be proc create_string_literal with "info"
    Let info_obj be proc get from Dict with ast, info_key

    Let title_key be proc create_string_literal with "title"
    Let title_value be proc get from Dict with info_obj, title_key
    proc assert_not_null with title_value, "Info has title"

    Let version_key be proc create_string_literal with "version"
    Let version_value be proc get from Dict with info_obj, version_key
    proc assert_not_null with version_value, "Info has version"

    proc print_string with "  ✓ Info validation tests passed"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles a paths object with a single path
("/users") that has both GET and POST operations, each with summary
and responses. The dual operations exercise the parser's per-verb
dispatch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parse the spec, then walk ast.paths./users to confirm both "get"
and "post" sub-keys exist.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Spec with /users GET and POST -> both operations present, passed
- Parser drops POST -> "Has POST operation" fails
- Parser fails on "/users" path key (mishandles "/") -> "Has /users path" fails
- Response status code parsing fails -> upstream null -> fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_paths":
    Note: Test paths object parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing paths parsing..."

    Note: Spec with paths and operations
    Let spec_with_paths be proc create_string_literal with "openapi: 3.0.0\ninfo:\n  title: Test API\n  version: 1.0.0\npaths:\n  /users:\n    get:\n      summary: Get all users\n      responses:\n        '200':\n          description: Success\n    post:\n      summary: Create user\n      responses:\n        '201':\n          description: Created\n"

    Let ast be proc parse_openapi from Parser with spec_with_paths

    Note: Should parse successfully
    proc assert_not_null with ast, "Spec with paths parsed"

    Note: Check paths
    Let paths_key be proc create_string_literal with "paths"
    Let paths_obj be proc get from Dict with ast, paths_key

    Let users_path_key be proc create_string_literal with "/users"
    Let users_path_item be proc get from Dict with paths_obj, users_path_key
    proc assert_not_null with users_path_item, "Has /users path"

    Note: Check operations
    Let get_key be proc create_string_literal with "get"
    Let get_operation be proc get from Dict with users_path_item, get_key
    proc assert_not_null with get_operation, "Has GET operation"

    Let post_key be proc create_string_literal with "post"
    Let post_operation be proc get from Dict with users_path_item, post_key
    proc assert_not_null with post_operation, "Has POST operation"

    proc print_string with "  ✓ Paths parsing tests passed"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles the components/schemas section with a
nested object schema (User with id:integer and name:string
properties). Required for any non-trivial API definition.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parse the spec, walk to ast.components.schemas.User, assert each
intermediate dict lookup returns non-null.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Spec with User schema -> all intermediate lookups succeed, passed
- Parser drops "components" -> "Has components object" fails
- Parser drops "schemas" subblock -> "Has schemas" fails
- Schema name "User" missing -> "Has User schema" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_components":
    Note: Test components object parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing components parsing..."

    Note: Spec with components
    Let spec_with_components be proc create_string_literal with "openapi: 3.0.0\ninfo:\n  title: Test API\n  version: 1.0.0\npaths: {}\ncomponents:\n  schemas:\n    User:\n      type: object\n      properties:\n        id:\n          type: integer\n        name:\n          type: string\n"

    Let ast be proc parse_openapi from Parser with spec_with_components

    Note: Should parse successfully
    proc assert_not_null with ast, "Spec with components parsed"

    Note: Check components
    Let components_key be proc create_string_literal with "components"
    Let components_obj be proc get from Dict with ast, components_key
    proc assert_not_null with components_obj, "Has components object"

    Note: Check schemas
    Let schemas_key be proc create_string_literal with "schemas"
    Let schemas_obj be proc get from Dict with components_obj, schemas_key
    proc assert_not_null with schemas_obj, "Has schemas"

    Let user_schema_key be proc create_string_literal with "User"
    Let user_schema be proc get from Dict with schemas_obj, user_schema_key
    proc assert_not_null with user_schema, "Has User schema"

    proc print_string with "  ✓ Components parsing tests passed"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: OpenAPI to HIR Translation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
End-to-end check from OpenAPI YAML to HIR. HIR contract is a dict
with type = "openapi_specification" and openapi/info/paths keys
preserved from the input.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Parse OpenAPI YAML with one GET /users path.
2. translate_openapi_to_hir(ast) -> hir; assert not null.
3. Dict lookups for type ("openapi_specification"), openapi, info, paths;
   each asserted non-null.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- One-path spec -> HIR with all 4 top-level fields, passed
- HIR.type != "openapi_specification" -> "HIR type correct" fails
- HIR missing openapi/info/paths -> respective assertion fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_openapi_to_hir":
    Note: Test OpenAPI AST to HIR translation

    proc print_string with "Testing OpenAPI→HIR translation..."

    Note: Parse OpenAPI spec
    Let spec be proc create_string_literal with "openapi: 3.0.0\ninfo:\n  title: Test API\n  version: 1.0.0\npaths:\n  /users:\n    get:\n      summary: Get users\n      responses:\n        '200':\n          description: Success\n"

    Let ast be proc parse_openapi from Parser with spec

    Note: Translate to HIR
    Let hir be proc translate_openapi_to_hir from ToHIR with ast

    Note: Check HIR structure
    proc assert_not_null with hir, "HIR created"

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc get from Dict with hir, type_key
    proc assert_not_null with type_value, "HIR has type field"

    Let expected_type be proc create_string_literal with "openapi_specification"
    proc assert_string_equals with type_value, expected_type, "HIR type correct"

    Note: Check that OpenAPI fields are preserved
    Let openapi_key be proc create_string_literal with "openapi"
    Let openapi_version be proc get from Dict with hir, openapi_key
    proc assert_not_null with openapi_version, "HIR has openapi version"

    Let info_key be proc create_string_literal with "info"
    Let info_obj be proc get from Dict with hir, info_key
    proc assert_not_null with info_obj, "HIR has info"

    Let paths_key be proc create_string_literal with "paths"
    Let paths_obj be proc get from Dict with hir, paths_key
    proc assert_not_null with paths_obj, "HIR has paths"

    proc print_string with "  ✓ OpenAPI→HIR translation tests passed"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: HIR to OpenAPI Generation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Reverse direction: construct a hand-built HIR for a minimal API
(openapi 3.0.0, info with title/version, empty paths) and assert
the emitter produces YAML containing "openapi", "info", "paths"
keywords.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Build HIR dict with type, openapi version, info subblock, empty paths.
2. generate_openapi_from_hir(hir) -> openapi_output.
3. Three string_contains assertions for "openapi", "info", "paths".
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Hand-built HIR -> output contains all three keywords, passed
- Emitter drops "openapi" -> "Generated YAML contains openapi" fails
- Emitter drops "info" -> "Generated YAML contains info" fails
- Emitter drops "paths" -> "Generated YAML contains paths" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_hir_to_openapi":
    Note: Test HIR to OpenAPI YAML generation

    proc print_string with "Testing HIR→OpenAPI generation..."

    Note: Create test HIR manually
    Let hir be proc create from Dict

    Note: Set type
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "openapi_specification"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Set openapi version
    Let openapi_key be proc create_string_literal with "openapi"
    Let openapi_version be proc create_string_literal with "3.0.0"
    proc set from Dict with hir, openapi_key, openapi_version

    Note: Create info object
    Let info_obj be proc create from Dict
    Let title_key be proc create_string_literal with "title"
    Let title_value be proc create_string_literal with "Test API"
    proc set from Dict with info_obj, title_key, title_value

    Let version_key be proc create_string_literal with "version"
    Let version_value be proc create_string_literal with "1.0.0"
    proc set from Dict with info_obj, version_key, version_value

    Let info_key be proc create_string_literal with "info"
    proc set from Dict with hir, info_key, info_obj

    Note: Create empty paths
    Let paths_obj be proc create from Dict
    Let paths_key be proc create_string_literal with "paths"
    proc set from Dict with hir, paths_key, paths_obj

    Note: Generate OpenAPI YAML
    Let openapi_output be proc generate_openapi_from_hir from FromHIR with hir

    Note: Check output contains key elements
    Let contains_openapi be proc string_contains with openapi_output, "openapi"
    proc assert_equals with contains_openapi, 1, "Generated YAML contains openapi"

    Let contains_info be proc string_contains with openapi_output, "info"
    proc assert_equals with contains_info, 1, "Generated YAML contains info"

    Let contains_paths be proc string_contains with openapi_output, "paths"
    proc assert_equals with contains_paths, 1, "Generated YAML contains paths"

    proc print_string with "  ✓ HIR→OpenAPI generation tests passed"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Round-Trip Translation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Full pipeline check: OpenAPI YAML -> AST -> HIR -> YAML. Multiple
contains-checks verify openapi version keyword, the API title string,
version string, and the path "/users" all survive both translation
directions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Parse original spec with description and one path.
2. translate_openapi_to_hir -> hir; generate_openapi_from_hir ->
   generated_spec.
3. Four string_contains assertions for "openapi", "Test API",
   "1.0.0", "/users".
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- One-path spec with description -> output contains all 4 strings, passed
- Emitter loses path -> "Round-trip contains users" fails (in full body)
- Emitter loses title -> "Round-trip contains title" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_round_trip":
    Note: Test OpenAPI → HIR → OpenAPI round-trip

    proc print_string with "Testing round-trip translation..."

    Note: Parse original OpenAPI spec
    Let original_spec be proc create_string_literal with "openapi: 3.0.0\ninfo:\n  title: Test API\n  version: 1.0.0\n  description: API for testing\npaths:\n  /users:\n    get:\n      summary: Get all users\n      responses:\n        '200':\n          description: Successful response\n"

    Let ast be proc parse_openapi from Parser with original_spec

    Note: OpenAPI → HIR
    Let hir be proc translate_openapi_to_hir from ToHIR with ast

    Note: HIR → OpenAPI
    Let generated_spec be proc generate_openapi_from_hir from FromHIR with hir

    Note: Check semantic equivalence (contains key elements)
    Let contains_openapi be proc string_contains with generated_spec, "openapi"
    proc assert_equals with contains_openapi, 1, "Round-trip contains openapi"

    Let contains_title be proc string_contains with generated_spec, "Test API"
    proc assert_equals with contains_title, 1, "Round-trip contains title"

    Let contains_version be proc string_contains with generated_spec, "1.0.0"
    proc assert_equals with contains_version, 1, "Round-trip contains version"

    Let contains_users be proc string_contains with generated_spec, "/users"
    proc assert_equals with contains_users, 1, "Round-trip contains /users path"

    Let contains_get be proc string_contains with generated_spec, "get"
    proc assert_equals with contains_get, 1, "Round-trip contains get operation"

    proc print_string with "  ✓ Round-trip translation tests passed"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Helper Functions
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Equality assertion. Failure prints just the message.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If actual != expected, print "FAILED: <message>" + newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "assert_equals" takes actual as Integer, expected as Integer, message as String:
    Note: Assert two integers are equal

    If actual is not equal to expected:
        proc print_string with "FAILED: "
        proc print_string with message
        proc print_string with " (expected: "
        proc print_integer with expected
        proc print_string with ", actual: "
        proc print_integer with actual
        proc print_string with ")"
        proc print_newline
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Null-pointer assertion. Most-used assertion in this file because
the test pattern is "lookup intermediate dict key, verify present".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If value == 0, print "FAILED: <message>" + newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "assert_not_null" takes value as Integer, message as String:
    Note: Assert value is not equal to 0

    If value is equal to 0:
        proc print_string with "FAILED: "
        proc print_string with message
        proc print_string with " (value is null)"
        proc print_newline
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
String equality assertion. Used to verify HIR type tag matches the
expected string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Call string_equals(actual, expected). If 0, print
"FAILED: <message> (expected '<expected>', got '<actual>')" + newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "assert_string_equals" takes actual as String, expected as String, message as String:
    Note: Assert two strings are equal

    Let are_equal be proc string_equals with actual, expected

    If are_equal is not equal to 1:
        proc print_string with "FAILED: "
        proc print_string with message
        proc print_string with " (expected: "
        proc print_string with expected
        proc print_string with ", actual: "
        proc print_string with actual
        proc print_string with ")"
        proc print_newline
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Byte-by-byte C-string equality comparator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walk index i upward, compare bytes via memory_get_byte. Mismatch
-> 0. Both null -> 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_equals" takes str1 as String, str2 as String returns Integer:
    Note: Compare two null-terminated C strings for equality

    Let i be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str1, i
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str2, i

        If c1 is not equal to c2:
            Return 0
        End If

        If c1 is equal to 0:
            Return 1  Note: Both strings ended at same point
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Naive substring search used by the emitter and round-trip tests
to verify YAML output preserves key strings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Empty needle -> 1. needle > haystack -> 0. Slide window over
haystack; all bytes match at some position -> 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_contains" takes haystack as String, needle as String returns Integer:
    Note: Check if haystack contains needle substring

    Let haystack_len be proc string_length from StringCore with haystack
    Let needle_len be proc string_length from StringCore with needle

    If needle_len is equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: Empty string is always contained
    End If

    If needle_len is greater than haystack_len:
        Return 0  Note: Needle can't be contained if longer than haystack
    End If

    Let i be 0
    Let max_i be haystack_len minus needle_len

    While i is less than or equal to max_i:
        Let matches be 1
        Let j be 0

        While j is less than needle_len:
            Let h_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with haystack, i plus j
            Let n_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with needle, j

            If h_char is not equal to n_char:
                Set matches to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Thin wrapper around StringCore.create_from_literal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forward to StringCore.create_from_literal(value).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_string_literal" takes value as String returns Integer:
    Note: Create string from string literal

    Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with value
End Process

Note: print_string, print_newline, and print_integer are bootstrap-runtime
Note: globals; test code calls them directly.
